12:["$","p",null,{"className":"x:not-first:mt-[1.25em] x:leading-7","children":["The ",["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"onboard_project"}]," skill is owned by Ava, but the ",["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"provision_discord"}]," skill that creates Discord channels is owned by Quinn. This is a chain: Ava calls Quinn via ",["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"chain[onboard_project]: quinn/provision_discord"}],"."]}]
13:["$","p",null,{"className":"x:not-first:mt-[1.25em] x:leading-7","children":["The reason is that Quinn has the Discord API client code and the knowledge of the standard channel structure (dev, alerts, releases). Ava handles the broader project provisioning logic (GitHub scaffold, Plane project creation, write-back to ",["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"projects.yaml"}],"). The chain keeps these responsibilities separate."]}]
14:["$","p",null,{"className":"x:not-first:mt-[1.25em] x:leading-7","children":["When the channel IDs come back from Discord, they are written to both ",["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"settings.json"}]," in the target repo and ",["$","code",null,{"className":"nextra-code","dir":"ltr","children":"projects.yaml"}]," in the protoWorkstacean repo. This makes the IDs available to both the agent running in the target repo context and the workstacean routing layer."]}]
